@Node "MsqlSumTimes()" "msql.library/MsqlSumTimes"

@{b}   NAME   @{ub}
           @{"MsqlSumTimes" Link "msql.guide/MsqlSumTimes"} --  Sum two mSQL time (V3)

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
           time = MsqlSumTimes(time1, time2)
           D0                   A0     A1

           char *MsqlSumTimes(char *, char *);

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
           The MsqlSumTimes() routine provides a mechanism for performing
           addition between two mSQL time formatted strings.  A literal
           addition of the values is returned to the calling routine in mSQL
           time format. As an example, calling @{"MsqlSumTimes" Link "msql.guide/MsqlSumTimes"} with the values
           "1:30:25" and "13:15:40" would return "14:46:05".

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
           time1 - a mSQL time formatted string.
           time2 - another mSQL time formatted string.

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
           time - a literal addition of time1 & time2.

@{b}   EXAMPLE@{ub}

@{b}   NOTES@{ub}
           The returned string is statically declared in the API so you must
           make a copy of it before you call the function again. Of course,
           since msql.library is a shared library, each process have his own
           buffer.

@{b}   BUGS@{ub}

@{b}   SEE ALSO@{ub}
           @{"MsqlDiffTimes()" Link "MsqlDiffTimes()"}, @{"MsqlDateOffset()" Link "MsqlDateOffset()"}, @{"MsqlDiffDates()" Link "MsqlDiffDates()"}

@EndNode

